Analysis of Factors on Wine Quality

Introduction

The purpose of this study is to look at two questions: First, can the quality score of a wine be determined by its chemical makeup? Can you determine the type of wine based on chemical makeup? Here is a glimpse of the data:

Variable Introduction

Fixed Acidity: This refers to the non-volatile acids that do not evaporate readily. A higher fixed acidity typically gives wine a more tart taste. Its an essential component for the structure and body of the wine. (continuous)

Volatile Acidity: Represents the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of a level can lead to an unpleasant vinegar taste. Its a key indicator of wine spoilage. (continuous)

Citric Acid: Found in small quantities in wine, its one of the fixed acids that can add freshness and flavor to wines. (continuous)

Residual Sugar: This is the sugar remaining after fermentation stops, affecting the sweetness of the wine. Wines can range from bone-dry to very sweet, depending on the residual sugar level. (continuous)

Chlorides: The amount of salt in the wine. High levels can lead to a salty taste, which is generally not desired in higher-quality wines. (continuous)

Free Sulfur Dioxide: The portion of sulfur dioxide that is not bound to other molecules; sulfur dioxide is used as a preservative to prevent spoilage and oxidation in wine. (continuous)

Total Sulfur Dioxide: This includes both free and bound sulfur dioxide. Its related to wine longevity and can influence the wines aroma and flavor. (continuous)

Density: Its related to the alcohol and sugar content of the wine. Wines with higher alcohol content will typically have a lower density-Possibly collinearity (continuous)

pH: Indicates the acidity of the wine on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3 and 4 on the pH scale. The pH affects flavor, color, and stability. (continuous)

Sulphates: These are compounds that can influence the fermentation process and act as antioxidants and preservatives. They may also affect the aroma and flavor profile of the wine. (continuous)

Alcohol: The alcohol content in wine, which results from the fermentation of sugars. Alcohol can influence the body, flavor, and overall balance of the wine. (continuous)

Wine_type: Red or white wine indicates the type of grape used (categorical)

Quality- Quality score from 1-10 (integer) (This is the target variable)

Explanatory Data Analysis 1

Column (data-width= 00)

Correlation

Column (data-width=400)

Summary

When looking at the correlation table. Alcohol has the highest of any of the explanatory variables with quality. Then it is followed with density. However alcohol and density are highly correlated so there may be evidence of co linearity here. It also, appears that volatile acidity and chlorides both have a negative relationship with quality. Due to the possible presence of co linearity and variable having a low impact on quality we will likely move forward with the Lasso model selection.

Explanation

It seems to follow the normality assumption very well and based on the Anderson darling test this assumption is met. However there is not a constant variance. There seems to be a linear pattern throughout the variance that violates this assumption. I have tried transformations and looked at outliers which did not effect this variance. Instead due to the low r squared and the lack of these conditions being met we will try and use wine type and see if we can solve the other research question.

Column

Base Model Result

First I converted the quality data to a binary data. I classified wine that is 5 and lower to be classified as poor wine and wine that is higher than 5 to be classified as good wine.

The Model had some evidence of co linearity earlier so I got the VIF scores for each variable.

The VIF score or Variance Inflation Factor is a measure that quantifies how much the variance of an estimated regression coefficient increases if your predictors are correlated. If there is no correlation among the predictors, the VIFs will be 1.

A VIF above 5 indicates that that variable has colinearity.

Therefore wine_type, density, and residual sugar were removed for colinearity.
